Overview the problem

A credit score is a quantitative tool for evaluating an individual’s ability and likelihood to repay debt. In areas such as loan and credit card applications, credit scoring determines whether a person can obtain credit, how much they can borrow, and the cost of borrowing. But the traditional credit scoring process relies on professional credit analysts manually reviewing loan applicants’ financial information, a time-consuming and inefficient process. We will categorise credit scores by classifying an individual’s credit as Good, Standard, or Poor. Using algorithms to analyse a large amount of personal data, including but not limited to income, employment and personal assets, we can use this data to quickly and fairly calculate a credit score for each applicant. This score reflects the likelihood that they will repay their loan in the future. In a competitive financial market, automated systems not only significantly improve the speed and accuracy of decision-making, but also ensure a consistent and unbiased process

Data cleaning

# convert the variable name to be lower case
names(df) <- tolower(names(df))

df_clean <- df

# function to convert all the missing data into "NA"
clean_non_alphanumeric <- function(df) {
  for (col in names(df)) {
    non_alphanumeric <- !grepl("[[:alnum:]]", df[[col]])
    df[[col]][non_alphanumeric] <- NA
  }
  return(df)
}
df_clean <- clean_non_alphanumeric(df)

# clean data points with symbol "@"
for (col in names(df_clean)) {
  if (any(grepl("@", df_clean[[col]]))) {
    df_clean[[col]][grepl("@", df_clean[[col]])] <- NA
  }
}

# convert "NM" in "payment_of_min_amount" to "NA"
df_clean$payment_of_min_amount[df_clean$payment_of_min_amount == "NM"] <- NA

# function to convert "credit_history_age" from categorical data to numeric data, measure by day
years_months_to_days <- function(years, months) {
  years_in_days <- years * 365
  months_in_days <- months * 30
  total_days <- years_in_days + months_in_days
  return(total_days)
}
df_clean$credit_history_age <- sapply(strsplit(df_clean$credit_history_age, " Years and | Months"), function(x) years_months_to_days(as.numeric(x[1]), as.numeric(x[2])))

# clean all numeric columns with data points like "-500", "_500" or "500_"
df_clean <- as.data.frame(lapply(df_clean, function(x) gsub("_", "", x, fixed = TRUE)))
rows_with_empty_values <- df_clean[rowSums(df_clean == "") > 0, ]

# convert selected columns to numeric
columns_to_convert <- c("id", "age", 
                        "annual_income", "monthly_inhand_salary", 
                        "num_bank_accounts", "num_credit_card",
                        "interest_rate", "num_of_loan",

df_clean[columns_to_convert] <- lapply(df_clean[columns_to_convert], as.numeric)

Since the dataset is messy and disordered, to commence cleaning the dataset, we started with cleaning the name. To standardizing the column names, converting them all to lowercase using the tolower() function to ensure consistency. One specific variable, “credit_history_age”, presented a categorical format: “22 Years and 1 Months”. While it held no predictive value, by extracting the numeric value and transform them to day variable, it could be used as a potential numeric feature, Additionally, we encounted inconsistencies in numeric data point such as: “500” and ”500”. These were inapropreiate and were removed using gsub(). Furthermore, the dataset erroneously treated all variables as character types. Correcting this, we converted all columns containing numeric values into actual numeric data types using as.numeric(). Following these data cleaining process, the dataset was ready for further anaylsis and modeling.

# Standardize the numerical data
scaled_data <- scale(df_numerical)

# Perform PCA
pca_result <- prcomp(scaled_data)

# Plot Eigenvalues
eigenvalues <- pca_result$sdev^2  
cumulative_variance <- cumsum(eigenvalues) / sum(eigenvalues)

# Plot the scree plot
plot(1:length(eigenvalues), cumulative_variance, type = "b",
xlab = "Number of Principal Components",
ylab = "Cumulative Variance Explained",
main = "Scree Plot for PCA")

we decided to performs Principal Component Analysis on the dataset. First, it standardizes the numerical data using the scale function to ensure that each variable has a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one, which is a common preprocessing step in PCA to give equal importance to all variables. Next, it applies PCA using the prcomp function, which calculates the principal components based on the standardized data. The eigenvalues, representing the amount of variance each principal component explains, are extracted from the PCA result. These eigenvalues are then used to calculate the cumulative variance explained by each principal component. Finally, the code generates a scree plot, a visual representation of the eigenvalues against the number of principal components, helping to determine the optimal number of components to retain based on the amount of variance they explain.

By visualizing a correlation heatmap, we can present the correlation between multiple variables. The color of each cell explains the strength and direction of the correlation, with darker colors indicating stronger correlations and lighter colors indicating weaker correlations.Positive correlations (when one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase) are represented by red, while negative correlations (when one variable increases, the other variable tends to decrease) are represented by blue. In Figure ?, “payment_behavior” and “monthly_balance” have the highest negatively correlated value at -0.61, while “delay_from_due_date” and “outstanding_debt” have the highest positive value at 0.57. The overall performance of the heatmap is considerable, with no highly correlated features, which refers to correlation coefficients whose magnitude lies between 0.7 and 0.9. Using highly correlated predictors in classification can result in unstable models, numerical errors, and poor prediction performance. Fortunately, our dataset does not have correlations that exceed 0.7, suggesting that there are likely no strong multicollinearity issues present. This makes the dataset suitable for various analytical techniques and modeling approaches without the concern of high collinearity potentially skewing results. It’s a positive sign for the robustness of our dataset and the potential effectiveness of the analyses.

Evaluation metrics

Since we are doing a classification problem, there are few approaches to check the performance of the model.

Confusion Matrix: Since we are predicting three class for the outcome variable “credit_score”, we can create a 3X3 confusion matrix and then calculate the TP, TN, FP, FN value for each class. The confusion matrix allows us to measure Recall, Precision, Accuracy, F1-score, and the AUC-ROC curve.

Precision, Recall and Accuracy: precision measures the percentage of predictions made by the model that are correct, while recall measures the percentage of relevant data points that are correctly identified by the model. Accuracy measures how often a machine learning model correctly predicts the outcome. We can use the metrics to test the accuracy of prediction and evaluate the performance of the model in a easy manner.

F1-score: F1 score is an alternative machine learning evaluation metric that assesses the predictive skill of a model by elaborating on its class-wise performance rather than an overall performance as done by accuracy. F1 score combines two competing metrics- precision and recall scores of a model. A high F1 score indicates a well-balanced performance, demonstrating that the model can concurrently attain high precision and high recall. A low F1 score signifies a trade-off between recall and precision, implying that the model has trouble striking that balance.

AUC curve: The Area under the ROC Curve (AUC) measures the total area beneath the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (ROC), which ranges from (0,0) to (1,1). This metric offers a aggregate evaluation of performance, summarizing how well the model distinguishes between different classes across all possible thresholds. AUC is particularly useful for balancing sensitivity and specificity. Higher AUC values indicate better differentiation between positive and negative classes, making it a useful metric for comparing models. Additionally, a high AUC suggests that the model is effective at making prediction.

How to split data and the choose of classifier

library(caret)
set.seed(5003)
train_indices <- createDataPartition(df_no_na$credit_score, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- df_no_na[train_indices, ]
test_data <- df_no_na[-train_indices, ]

With the credit_score as the target variable, we will split the dataset into train_data and test_data.

For the classifier, our dataset aims to predict individuals’ credit scores (good, standard, poor) based on various factors. We’ll discuss the suitability of four classification algorithms for this task:

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN): Effective for multi-class prediction and similarity-based classification. Logistic Regression (LR): Classic, interpretable, and suitable for analyzing feature impact. Support Vector Machine (SVM): Ideal for high-dimensional data and complex decision boundaries. AdaBoosting: Ensemble method handling imbalanced classes and focusing on difficult instances. Each algorithm offers unique strengths for accurately classifying credit scores based on features like monthly salary, credit history, and payment behavior. The choice depends on factors like model complexity, interpretability, and performance requirements, and a thorough evaluation is crucial for selecting the best-suited algorithm.
